.TH JENNIFER-TINY 1 "2026" "Jennifer" "Jennifer Programming Language"
.SH NAME
jennifer-tiny \- Jennifer programming language interpreter (TinyGo build)
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B jennifer-tiny
.I subcommand
.RI [ args ...]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B jennifer-tiny
is the TinyGo-compiled variant of the Jennifer interpreter, shipped
alongside the default
.BR jennifer (1)
binary. Same source code, same language surface; the TinyGo build is
smaller and embeddable at the cost of two host-feature gaps:
.IP \(bu 2
external-program execution
.RB ( os.run ", " os.spawn ", " os.wait ", " os.poll ", " os.kill )
returns a friendly runtime error pointing the user at
.BR jennifer .
.IP \(bu 2
the whole
.B net
library (TCP/UDP sockets, DNS lookups) returns the same friendly error.
.PP
Both gaps come from TinyGo's runtime, not the language:
.B os/exec
isn't implemented, and TinyGo's
.B net
package requires a netdev driver that
.B jennifer-tiny
doesn't register. Use
.B jennifer-tiny
when binary size or embeddability matters more than these features
(embedded devices, minimal container images, small-footprint
scripting hosts).
.PP
.B jennifer-tiny
is a run-only interpreter: it supports
.B run
and
.BR repl ,
but omits the development subcommands
.RB ( tokens ", " ast ", " fmt ", " lint ", " profile ", " test ", " serve ),
which live only in the default
.BR jennifer (1)
binary and return a friendly error here. The language surface is
otherwise identical to
.BR jennifer (1) ";"
see that page for the full reference.
.SH "SEE ALSO"
.BR jennifer (1),
.UR https://github.com/jennifer-language/jennifer
.UE
